<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910621-0152</DOCNO><DOCID>910621-0152.</DOCID><HL>   L.B. Foster Agrees   To Buy Assets of Unit   Of Harmon Industries</HL><DATE>06/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   FSTRA HRMN</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>DIVERSIFIED INDUSTRIAL (IDD)OIL EQUIPMENT AND SERVICES (OIE)PETROLEUM (PET)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>KANSAS (KS)MISSOURI (MO)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   PITTSBURGH -- L.B. Foster Co. said it signed a letter ofintent to purchase the assets of Cedrite Technologies Inc., asubsidiary of Harmon Industries Inc.   Cedrite recycles discarded railroad ties to formreconstituted ties that are reused instead of beingincinerated or dumped in landfills. Because railroad ties arechemically treated, they may pose an environmental hazardwhen discarded, said Lee B. Foster, president and chiefexecutive officer of L.B. Foster, which makes rail,construction and tubular products.</LP><TEXT>   The Cedrite plant, located in Kansas City, Kan., has thecapacity to recycle 600,000 ties a year; the process consumestwo used ties for every one reconstituted tie, Mr. Fostersaid.   Mr. Foster declined to discuss terms of the agreement toacquire Cedrite, whose parent company, Harmon of BlueSprings, Mo., supplies signalling, communications and controlproducts for the railroad industry.</TEXT></DOC>